    <h2>Example 3</h2>

    <p>Similar to the previous example, we use here an <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/docs/Web/HTTP/Methods" data-linktype="external">HTTP GET</a> method, invoked by appending <code>/HelloWorld/Welcome/</code> to the URL:</p>
    <pre><code class="lang-csharp">using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;
using System.Text.Encodings.Web;

namespace AspNetCoreMvc_Mvc.Controllers
{
    public class HelloWorldController : Controller
    {
        // GET: /HelloWorld/WelcomeByName/
        public string WelcomeByName(string name = "Rick", int numTimes = 5)
        {
            return HtmlEncoder.Default.Encode($"Hello {name}, NumTimes is: {numTimes}");
        }
    }
}
</code></pre>

    <p>Press this button to envoke the example code: <a class="button whitespace_nowrap" asp-area="" target="_blank" asp-controller="HelloWorld" asp-action="WelcomeByName">Run example 3</a></p>

    <p>The preceding code:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Does not use any query string in the URL to pass values for the named parameters. Instead, it uses the C# optional-parameter feature to indicate that the <code>name</code> parameter defaults to 'Nick' and the <code>numTimes</code> parameter defaults to 1 if no value is passed for those parameters.</li>
        <li>Uses <code>HtmlEncoder.Default.Encode</code> to protect the app from malicious input, such as through JavaScript.</li>
        <li>Uses <a href="https://docs.microsoft.comhttps://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/articles/csharp/language-reference/keywords/interpolated-strings" data-linktype="absolute-path">Interpolated Strings</a> in <code>$&quot;Hello {name}, NumTimes is: {numTimes}&quot;</code>.</li>
    </ul>

